      "?bird wdt:P31 wd:Q205068 .", "><!-- P31 is instance of, Q205068 is bird--> <!-- P31 is the property for instance of, and Q205068 is the class for birds. So this line selects all entities that are birds. --> <!-- I need to filter these birds based on their conservation status. The next step is to find the property that represents the conservation status in Wikidata. After checking, P10347 is the property for conservation status. Now, I need to identify the value for critically endangered. Looking it up, Q586293 is the concept for critically endangered species. So the next line should filter where the bird's conservation status is Q586293. --> " ,
      "?bird wdt:P10347 wd:Q586293 .", "><!-- P10347 is conservation status, Q586293 is critically endangered--> <!-- Now I need to limit the results to only resources, which means no labels or descriptions. In SPARQL, using SELECT ?bird will return the resource URIs. To ensure that, I can omit any projections for labels or other properties. --> " ,

Translate the question “Give me all actors starring in movies directed by and starring William Shatner.” into a SPARQL query using a Knowledge Graph. Have the query return only resources. Provide only the generated SPARQL query. The possible entities and properties are: 
kg:3840 is director
kg:6889 is William Shatner
kg:7140 is cast member
kg:6889 is William Shatner
kg:7140 is cast member
response:
{ "query": [
    "SELECT ?actor WHERE {",
    "  ?movie kg:3840 kg:6889 .", ">// movie directed by William Shatner (kg:6889)"
    ,
    "  ?movie kg:7140 ?actor .", ">// movie has cast member ?actor"
    ,
    "  FILTER (?actor != kg:6889) ." , ">// exclude William Shatner himself"
    ,
    "} "
  ]
}
